Welcome!

The aim of this project is to enable the creation of a multilingual low-cost eye-tracking dataset, designed to make artificial intelligence-based language technologies fair and transparent.

You can read more about the project here.

For questions about the experiment please contact the project leader: Nora Hollenstein, nora.hollenstein@hum.ku.dk

stimulus:
Experiment Instructions

Expected duration: 20-30 mins (including small pauses during calibration)

This experiment uses your camera for eye tracking. In order to participate you must allow the experiment to use your camera.

We would like to remind you that we are only collecting the information about where you look on your screen, no video is recorded.

Please follow the instructions below.

Camera Instructions:

Keep your head still and try to read by only moving your eyes when performing the different tasks. To avoid unnecessary movements, keep your hands close to the keyboard.

2. Keep any light sources in front of you, so the webcam can clearly detect your face. Please avoid having a window behind you.

3. Disable notifications to avoid distractions.

4. Close any unnecessary applications or tabs as the eye-tracking software is quite demanding.

To continue with the experiment, we will check your browser to confirm that it supports the eye-tracking software.

stimulus:
Task Instructions:

There is two tasks present in the experiment:

Task 1, the normal reading task

You will be presented with a paragraph you should read from beginning to end as naturally as you would read any other text. There is no time limit. After finishing and moving to the next screen, you will need to answer a comprehension question about the paragraph.

Task 2, the information searching task,

You will be presented with a question which you should read carefully. On the next screen, a paragraph will be presented which contains the answer to the question shown before. Read the text until you have found the answer. There is no time limit. On the following screen, you will then see the same question again. At this point, you will need to provide an answer based on the paragraph you read.

Each of these steps is preceded by a black fixation cross in the middle of the screen, which you should focus on between steps. When done reading texts, you will press Spacebar on your keyboard to move to the next screen.

After two trials, we will recalibrate the eye-tracker to ensure better data quality. You may take a small pause before these re-calibrations.

You will now fill out a short questionnaire with some data needed for the experiment.

stimulus:
Task 1 (normal reading task):

We're ready for the first task now.

Each step is preceded by a black fixation cross in the middle of the screen, you should fixate it while it is being displayed.

You'll be given a text to read in your own time. Once you finished reading, click the Spacebar key on your keyboard.

On the next screen, you will be given one statement or question about the text.

If given a statement determine if it is True or False, by clicking on the corresponding button with your mouse.

Otherwise, if it's a question you will need enter your answer based on what you read in the paragraph on the previous screen.

The answer shouldn't be too long, normally between 1 to 5 words.

In total, you will perform 5 trials.

Remember, there will be a quick calibration after the 2nd and 4th trial, where you may also take a small break.

stimulus:
Task 2 (information searching task):

We're ready for the second task now.

Each step is preceded by a black fixation cross in the middle of the screen, you should focus your gaze on it while it is being displayed.

You'll be given one question to a short paragraph. You will first read the question.

Take your time to read the question and click continue when you are ready to read the paragraph.

The paragraph will then be shown, and it contains the answer to the question you've seen.

Take your time to read the text and find the answer. When ready click the Spacebar key on your keyboard.

You will see the question again. Now please answer the question based on what you read.

Remember, the answer shouldn't be too long, normally between 1 to 5 words.

In total, you will perform 5 trials.

Remember, there will be quick calibration steps after the 1st and 3rd trial, where you may also take a small break.
